<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1869-07-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1869-07-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="405" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d405">
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Barlow</persName>,
                                    United States marshal, to Mr. <persName type="to">Hoar</persName>, Attorney-General.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <dateline><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi></placeName>,
                                    <date calendar="gregorian" when="1869-07-02"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 2, 1869</date>.</dateline>
                            <p rend="flushleft"><hi rend="smallcaps">Attorney-General</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington:</hi></p>
                            <p>There are not to exceed one hundred and seventy-five men. The balance
                                escaped ashore before capture. Who shall feed them? They will starve
                                unless some one does. Who must take charge of them, I or the
                                admiral? Please answer. Unless these men are discharged at once, I
                                learn that a <hi rend="italic">habeas corpus</hi> will be sued out
                                for them. What return can be made to it?</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>FRANCIS C. BARLOW,<lb/><hi rend="italic">United States
                                        Marshal.</hi></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>